sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583108
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: pRha + CsgA with Hydroxyapatite-affinity tag & pTet + RFP
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Upon induction with rhamnose, a fusion protein of CsgA with a hydroxyapatite affinity tag is expressed. The CsgA protein monomers can aggregate to form amyloid nanofibres. The affinity tag is supposed to increase adhesive properties of the biofilm created as a result of the CsgA induction. In order to better visualize the individual cells in the biofilm, we added the constitutive expression of RFP to our plasmid in a different operon. For our design, we took advantage of the double terminator present in the biobrick I13521 by placing it in front of our genes.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stefan Robert Marsden
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The DNA was synthesized. The sequence originates from the genomic DNA of E. coli K-12 MG1655 (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/949055).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: For our design, we took advantage of the double terminator present in the biobrick I13521 by placing it in front of our genes.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I13521
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Constitutive on mRFP (positive control)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: jkm

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583102
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part was synthesized. The rhamnose promoter was used by the iGEM 2014 TU Delft team and originally added by the iGEM12 Paris Bettencourt team. RBS and CsgA originate from E. coli K-12 MG1655. The nucleotides encoding for the second and third amino acid of the CsgA gene were changed to optimize synthesis success. (silent mutations). Upon induction with rhamnose, CsgA is expressed and exported into the extracellular space. There, the membrane protein CsgB can trigger the CsgA protein monomers to aggregate and form amyloid nanofibres.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stefan Robert Marsden, Hector Sanguesa Ferrer
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The DNA was synthesized. The sequence originates from the genomic DNA of E. coli K-12 MG1655 (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/949055).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The stop codon needed to be removed from CsgA to add the N-terminal hydroxyapatite affinity tag.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: mRFP1
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: **highly** engineered mutant of red fluorescent protein from Discosoma striata (coral)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: monomeric RFP: Red Fluorescent Protein. Excitation peak: 584 nm Emission peak: 607 nm
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Drew Endy
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Campbell et al., PNAS v99 p7877 URL
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
TAATAA double stop codon added (DE).
Four silent mutations made to remove three EcoRI sites and one PstI site: A28G, A76G, A349G, G337A.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0010
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcriptional terminator consisting of a 64 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Randy Rettberg

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: p(tetR)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Sequence for pTet inverting regulator driven by the TetR protein.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: June Rhee, Connie Tao, Ty Thomson, Louis Waldman
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Lutz, R., Bujard, H., Nucleic Acids Research (1997) 25, 1203-1210.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: BBa_R0040 TetR-Regulated Promoter is based on a cI promoter. It has been modified to include two TetR binding sites and the BioBrick standard assembly head and tail restriction sites.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: RBS based on Elowitz repressilator.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K914003
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: L-rhamnose-inducible promoter is capable of high-level recombinant protein expression in the presence of L-rhamnose, it is also tightly regulated in the absence of L-rhamnose by the addition of D-glucose.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Denis Samuylov
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Amplification of the plasmid pJOE3075 (Dr. Altenbuchner).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: One base pair modified (90: A -> T) to avoid EcoRI site. Mutation made in a less conserved base pair.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This scar originates from the part BBa_K1316015, on which the composite part BBa_K1583100 is based.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583014
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: CsgA missing the stop codon for creation of fusion proteins
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part was designed to create a fusion protein of CsgA with Mfp3 (mussel foot protein). This protein has got high adhesive properties towards wet polar surfaces. Like this, an amyloid nanowire with high binding properties is created.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stefan Robert Marsden
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The DNA was synthesized. The sequence originates from the genomic DNA of E. coli K-12 MG1655 (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/949055).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The stop codon was deleted to create a fusion protein.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
A linker with the protein sequence GSGGSG was placed in between the CsgA and the affinity tag for increased performance reasons. The design was based on the paper "Programmable biofilm-based materials from engineered curli nanofibres"[1]
1. Nguyen, P. Q., Botyanszki, Z., Tay, P. K. R., & Joshi, N. S. (2014). Programmable biofilm-based materials from engineered curli nanofibres. Nature communications, 5.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance:
The DNA was synthesized. The sequence of CsgA originates from the genomic DNA of E. coli K-12 MG1655.(http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/949055). The design was based on the paper "Programmable biofilm-based materials from engineered curli nanofibres"[1]
1. Nguyen, P. Q., Botyanszki, Z., Tay, P. K. R., & Joshi, N. S. (2014). Programmable biofilm-based materials from engineered curli nanofibres. Nature communications, 5.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
We followed the design of "Programmable biofilm-based materials from engineered curli nanofibres"[1]
1. Nguyen, P. Q., Botyanszki, Z., Tay, P. K. R., & Joshi, N. S. (2014). Programmable biofilm-based materials from engineered curli nanofibres. Nature communications, 5.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583060
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part generates a peptide tag which shows high adhesive properties towards hydroxyapatite, a main component of teeth.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stefan Robert Marsden
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance:
The sequence was obtained from the paper "Identification of a Highly Specific Hydroxyapatite-binding Peptide using Phage Display" [1]
1. M. Roy, S. Stanley, E. Amis, M. Becker, Adv. Mater., 2008, 20, 1830-1836.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: No specific design considerations were made.
